-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury </em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work. </strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects! </strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy </strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns! </strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats </em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals! </strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts </strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;3h 31m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-12-circle-skirts/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-12-circle-skirts/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-04T17:03:38+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-07T18:45:26+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 12. Circle Skirts."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 12. Circle Skirts."><meta itemprop="description" content="There are no doubts that they are the top favorite skirts in wedding fashion! All full multi-layer skirts sewn with lightweight fabrics are cut based on a circle shape"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 12. Circle Skirts.</h1><p><strong>We have moved to a new chapter dedicated to circle skirts. </strong></p><p><b>There are no doubts that they are the top favorite&nbsp;skirts in wedding fashion! </b>All full multi-layer skirts sewn with lightweight fabrics are cut based on a circle shape.</p><p>On the one hand, there is such a great variety of skirts that one does not know where to look first. And, on the other hand, they are so simple to calculate and cut that it seems like there is no point in talking about them much.</p><p>We cannot ignore the subject entirely though.</p><p>There are certain moments worth discussing.</p><p><strong>Let us start from the full-circle skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the formulae for their calculation. </strong></p><p><strong>We know it from school maths lessons that the perimeter of a circle is calculated as 2πR where</strong></p><p><strong>π</strong> = 3.14 (it is a constant value),</p><p>And <strong>R</strong> is the radius, which is what we are supposed to find.</p><p><strong>We can find the radius of the waist opening if we know the Waist Circumference. </strong></p><p><strong>For a full-circle (full sweep) skirt:</strong> divide Waist Circumference by 2π.</p><p><strong>For a half-circle skirt:</strong>&nbsp; divide Waist Circumference by π.</p><p><strong>If the waist is supposed to be gathered, </strong>multiply Waist Circumference by the gathering ratio.</p><p><strong>Next, add skirt length to the found waist opening radius to find a radius for cutting the bottom edge. </strong></p><p><strong>It would be simple if we were not limited by the width of fabric. </strong></p><p>Standard fabric width is 150-155cm in the best case. There are materials with a width of 140cm and lace fabrics are normally as narrow as 120-130cm.</p><p><strong>And it is where questions begin to arise. </strong>How to cut a full sweep skirt or a half-circle skirt from fabric of a limited width? And considering you need to gather the waist? How much fabric will you need?</p><p><strong>Let us start from simple cases when the size of the skirt allows it to fit into the width of fabric. </strong></p><p><strong>First of all, I want to remind you the rules of efficient use of fabric for cutting the full sweep skirt. </strong>This issue was described in great detail in our <em>Wedding Skirts </em>published back in 2011.</p><p><strong>Suppose we have fabric with a width of 150cm and we need to figure out how much of it we need to sew a full sweep skirt with the following parameters: </strong></p><p>Waist Circumference - 74cm,</p><p>Skirt Length - 120cm.</p><p><strong>Let us find the radius of the waist opening using the existing formula. </strong></p><p><strong>R =</strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image002.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp;= 11.8 cm ≈ 12 cm</strong></p><p><strong>Then the large radius of the skirt is as follows: </strong></p><p><strong>R(L) = 12cm + 120cm = 132cm </strong></p><p>I don’t add any allowances for finishing the edges of the skirt because the full sweep skirt is usually cut with some extra length in case the fabric stretches out or you need to re-shape it because of its bias-cut areas.</p><p><strong>Below is a schematic drawing of the most efficient layout for cutting the full sweep skirt. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Our task is to figure out fabric consumption. </strong></p><p><strong>We basically need to find the length of one leg (b) of the right triangle ABC </strong>knowing the length of the other leg (a), which equals the width of fabric (150cm), and the hypotenuse (c) calculated as follows:</p><p>2R(L)&nbsp; = 2 х 132cm = 264cm</p><p>I will use the well-known <strong>right triangle formula</strong> which says that the sum of the squares of the lengths of the legs is equal to the square of the hypotenuse.</p><p>In other words:</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image006.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp;+ </strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image008.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp;= </strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image010.png" alt=""></p><p>Wherefore,<br><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image012.png" alt="" height="20"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image008.png" alt="">&nbsp;=<br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image014.png" alt="">&nbsp;-<br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image016.png" alt="">&nbsp;= (264 х 264) - (150 х 150) = 47,196 square centimeters.</p><p>In this case, leg (b) is calculated as follows:</p><p><strong>b</strong> =<br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image018.png" alt="">&nbsp;= <strong>217cm</strong></p><p><strong>Since the fabric is supposed to be folded, total fabric consumption will be: </strong></p><p>217cm х 2 = 434cm</p><p>As the result, we will cut one half-circle piece and two quarter-circles. The cut edge will be the central back edge of the skirt and the selvages will be its side seam edges.</p><p><strong>Of course, 434cm is a hypothetic perfect value. In reality, it will take about 450cm to cut this skirt considering possible distortions and related adjustments. </strong>This amount should be enough to cut a waistband and to protect yourself from various unforeseen circumstances.</p><p><strong>And now, let us calculate fabric consumption for a half-circle skirt with the same parameters. </strong></p><p><strong>We use the same formula to find the waist opening radius. </strong>It is exactly two times longer than on the full sweep skirt.</p><p><strong>R =</strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image020.png" alt=""><strong>&nbsp; ≈ 24cm</strong></p><p><strong>Then the large radius of the skirt is as follows: </strong></p><p><strong>R(L) = 24cm + 120cm = 144cm</strong></p><p><strong>The layout is very simple (see the red line). </strong>The fold line and the selvages stay where they were, only this time the selvage at the bottom marks the central back edge and not the side edge.</p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>It is clear from the layout that the full fabric consumption can be determined by two large radii: </strong></p><p><strong>2 х R(L) = 2 х 144cm = 288cm ≈ 300cm</strong></p><p><strong>Let us solve an interesting task. </strong>Suppose we want to gather the waist of the calculated full sweep skirt.</p><p><strong>What is the biggest possible gathering ratio considering the width of our fabric? </strong></p><p><strong>If the fabric has a width of 150cm and the skirt is 120cm long, then the difference is: </strong></p><p>150cm – 120cm = 30cm</p><p><strong>We know the waist opening radius: R = 12cm.</strong></p><p><strong>Therefore, the biggest possible gathering ratio will be: </strong></p><p><strong>GR = 30cm / 12cm = 2.5</strong></p><p><strong>So the gathering ratio is 2.5. This is as big as it gets for a 120cm long skirt with a Waist Circumference of 74cm sewn with fabric with a width of 150cm. </strong>Needless to say that it will be different for a skirt of different parameters.</p><p><strong>Fabric consumption is determined the same way as before, only this time you need to account for the gathering ratio. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2012.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p><p>Now the gathering ratio is accounted for in the waist opening radius. <strong>R = 30cm.</strong></p><p><strong>Therefore, R(L) = 30cm + 120cm = 150cm.</strong></p><p><strong>Total fabric consumption in this case will make 520cm. </strong></p><p><strong>The demonstrated method of calculating fabric consumption is quite simple and precise but there is one very important requirement which you must keep in mind! </strong></p><p><strong>Fabric consumption per layer (the length of leg (b)) must be greater than the length of the large radius R(L). </strong></p><p><strong>It happens that this condition is not always fulfilled when calculating short full sweep skirts. </strong></p><p><strong>In that case, R(L) is adopted as fabric consumption per layer, while full fabric consumption is considered equal to 2 х R(L).</strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation&nbsp;Tables with Fixed Parameters:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlinaFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a></strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><h3>Skirt Patterns:</h3><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Patterns/flaredSkirt.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.